50|$|Theoretically, LGD is {{calculated}} in different ways, {{but the most}} popular is 'Gross' LGD, where total losses are divided by exposure at default (EAD). Another method is to divide Losses by the unsecured portion of a credit line (where security covers a portion of EAD). This is known as 'Blanco' LGD. If <b>collateral</b> <b>value</b> is zero in the last case then Blanco LGD is equivalent to Gross LGD. Different types of statistical methods {{can be used to}} do this.|$|E
